Conditions {{arxiv_2110_13883_FO0138||FO}}-{{arxiv_2110_13883_FO0139||FO}} in Model (ref) are very light requirements. If Cond. 1 would be violated, our estimator could still detect that there is no shared information between {{arxiv_2110_13883_FO0140||FO}} and {{arxiv_2110_13883_FO0141||FO}}, but there would be little point in modeling the generative process from a manifold learning perspective. Similarly, Cond. 3 requires that all variables in the low-dimensional representation are contributing to the shared information about {{arxiv_2110_13883_FO0142||FO}} and {{arxiv_2110_13883_FO0143||FO}}. Any subsets of variables not fulfilling this requirement would be modeled within the individual factor. Last, Cond. 2 assures that {{arxiv_2110_13883_FO0144||FO}} can be recovered from {{arxiv_2110_13883_FO0145||FO}}, as shown in Proposition (ref). This is a standard assumption in manifold learning: the low-dimensional manifold can be modeled as a homeomorphism of the ambient space or a subspace of it [cayton:05:manifold-learning-algorithms].